What do you prefer when writing promises?

``` javascript
caches.open('cache').then(function (cache) {
  cache.put(event.request, clonedResponse);
});
```

---

``` javascript
caches.open('cache')
  .then(function (cache) {
    cache.put(event.request, clonedResponse);
  });
```

Some things that could alter the answer could be the `catch`, i found the second one clearer when using `catch`, but i also find the first one more clear when `catch` is ommited. Also if the promise is long like: `someObjectThatContains.someMethod(SomeVariable)`, chaining `then` in the same line can slip past the `then` method.

Anyway, Do you have preference?

What about trailing commas here?

``` javascript
const hero = (
  firstName,
  lastName,
  birthYear,
  superPower, // <-- this one
) => {
  // ....
};
```

It needs [http://babeljs.io/docs/plugins/syntax-trailing-function-commas/](http://babeljs.io/docs/plugins/syntax-trailing-function-commas/) and it's based on [this proposal](https://github.com/jeffmo/es-trailing-function-commas)

Does AirBnB encourages the use of trailing commas here?

Hello, This is a question, not a issue.

```
